===Etymology===
First attested in Late {{etyl|enm}} as {{m|enm|lepe}} {{m|enm|ȝere}} and {{m|enm|yere}} but probably a much older formation related to the {{etyl|ang|-}} {{m|ang|mónan hlýp}} and {{etyl|la|-}} {{m|la|saltus lunae}} used in reckoning lunar months on a 19-year cycle. The name is presumably related the phenomenon that any fixed date of a 365-day calendar advances one weekday each year but every date of a 366-day year (on modern reckonings after February 29) advances by two weekdays instead.<ref>[http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/106711 "'leap year, ''n.''"], in the ''Oxford English Dictionary'', Oxford: Oxford University Press.</ref> For example, Christmas (December 25) fell on a Saturday in 2004, a Sunday in 2005, a Monday in 2006, and a Tuesday in 2007 but then "leapt" over Wednesday to fall on a Thursday in 2008.

